Some good guidelines include:
-Use clear title hierarchies;
-write in sentences that are short and concise;
-break up your content into short paragraphs of about 3-5 sentences;
-use hyperlinks to point to further information and original research or data;
-use the "inverted pyramid" structure for your texts: start with the most important information, then expand on and supplement this information with details and finally add non-crucial background information. You can end the text with a call-to-action.

It is also important to use design to support the legibility and reader-friendliness:
-Use fonts and font sizes that are easily legible on screens (see “Choose accessible colour combinations and fonts”);
-consistently use different font sizes to support title hierarchies;
-choose the width of your paragraphs so that each text line does not contain more than 75 and not less than 45 characters.

Some good guidelines include:
-Know your audience and know which terms your audience understands;
-Use simple terms
-Write in short sentences and paragraphs
-aim for a 10th to 12th grade reading level;
-avoid jargon and abbreviations.
